---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout>
  <div class="container">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4">Interesting Articles</h1>
    <p class="mb-8 text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">
      Research papers and articles I've referenced or found particularly insightful.
    </p>

    <div class="space-y-8">
      
      <div class="p-6 border rounded-lg bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
        <h3 class="text-base font-medium mb-2 whitespace-nowrap overflow-hidden text-ellipsis">
          <a href="https://12factor.net/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">
            The Twelve-Factor App Methodology
          </a>
        </h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-3">
          Adam Wiggins (2017) - Heroku (Always Free)
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          A methodology for building software-as-a-service applications that are portable, scalable, and maintainable. These twelve principles have become fundamental guidelines for modern application development, covering everything from configuration management to process scaling.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="p-6 border rounded-lg bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
        <h3 class="text-base font-medium mb-2 whitespace-nowrap overflow-hidden text-ellipsis">
          <a href="https://github.com/donnemartin/system-design-primer" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">
            The System Design Primer
          </a>
        </h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-3">
          Donne Martin (2024) - GitHub (Open Source)
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          A comprehensive resource for learning system design concepts with examples, diagrams, and exercises. This repository covers everything from scalability principles to distributed systems architecture, making complex topics accessible through clear explanations and visual aids.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="p-6 border rounded-lg bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
        <h3 class="text-base font-medium mb-2 whitespace-nowrap overflow-hidden text-ellipsis">
          <a href="https://medium.com/@maximebeauchemin/functional-data-engineering-a-modern-paradigm-for-batch-data-processing-2327ec32c42a" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">
            Functional Data Engineering — A Modern Paradigm
          </a>
        </h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-3">
          Maxime Beauchemin (2016) - Medium (Free)
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          Written by the creator of Apache Airflow, this article outlines principles for building reliable, testable data pipelines. It introduces concepts like idempotency, immutability, and functional programming principles applied to data engineering, which have become foundational to modern data pipeline design.
        </p>
      </div>
        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          This technical specification established how healthcare documents should be structured and shared electronically. Before this standard, medical records were like different languages that couldn't talk to each other. HL7 CDA created a common format for things like lab results, discharge summaries, and medical histories, making it possible for different healthcare systems to exchange patient information safely and accurately.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="p-6 border rounded-lg bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
        <h3 class="text-base font-medium mb-2 whitespace-nowrap overflow-hidden text-ellipsis">
          <a href="https://www.healthaffairs.org/doi/10.1377/hlthaff.w5.10" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">
            The value of health care information exchange and interoperability
          </a>
        </h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-3">
          Walker, J., Pan, E., Johnston, D., et al. (2005) - Health Affairs
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          This influential paper made the economic case for why healthcare systems should share data with each other. The authors calculated that better information sharing could save the U.S. healthcare system billions of dollars annually by reducing duplicate tests, preventing medical errors, and improving care coordination. It helped justify the massive investments in healthcare IT infrastructure that followed.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="p-6 border rounded-lg bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
        <h3 class="text-base font-medium mb-2 whitespace-nowrap overflow-hidden text-ellipsis">
          <a href="https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/200501" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">
            Role of computerized physician order entry systems in facilitating medication errors
          </a>
        </h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-3">
          Koppel, R., Metlay, J. P., Cohen, A., et al. (2005) - JAMA
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          This surprising study found that electronic prescribing systems, while solving some problems, actually created new types of medication errors. The researchers discovered that poorly designed computer interfaces could lead doctors to accidentally order the wrong medications or doses. It was an important reality check showing that just digitizing healthcare processes isn't automatically better - the design and implementation matter enormously.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="p-6 border rounded-lg bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
        <h3 class="text-base font-medium mb-2 whitespace-nowrap overflow-hidden text-ellipsis">
          <a href="https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1968-07393-001" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">
            Bystander intervention in emergencies: Diffusion of responsibility
          </a>
        </h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-3">
          Darley, J. M., & Latané, B. (1968) - Journal of Personality and Social Psychology
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          This classic psychology experiment revealed the "bystander effect" - the more people who witness an emergency, the less likely any individual is to help. The researchers found that responsibility gets diluted when spread across multiple people. I reference this when discussing how complex healthcare systems with multiple automated decision-makers can obscure accountability when things go wrong.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="p-6 border rounded-lg bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
        <h3 class="text-base font-medium mb-2 whitespace-nowrap overflow-hidden text-ellipsis">
          <a href="https://studenttheses.universiteitleiden.nl/access/item%3A2661526/view" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400 hover:underline">
            Healthcare Data Interoperability: Challenges and Opportunities in Digital Health Integration
          </a>
        </h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-3">
          Peterson, L. (2024) - Universiteit Leiden Student Theses
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          This recent thesis provides a comprehensive examination of current challenges in healthcare data sharing and integration. It explores both the technical hurdles (like incompatible data formats) and policy barriers (like privacy regulations) that prevent healthcare systems from seamlessly sharing patient information. The work offers practical recommendations for overcoming these obstacles in modern digital health implementations.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
